{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585877","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585877"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:20:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:20:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15027"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15027","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15027"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.19,0.16,0.06,0.42]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7715"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67174"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7715","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7715"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15027"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52630"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4932"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8115"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18847"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18850"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67174","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67174"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ENephrogenic systemic fibrosis is a rare but serious condition that causes fibrosis of the skin, joints, and internal organs. It primarily affects patients with severe kidney disease.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following agents is most strongly associated with the development of nephrogenic systemic fibrosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Non-steroidal anti-inflammatory medicines","Gadolinium-based contrast media","Iodinated contrast media","Beta-lactam antibiotics","Aminoglycoside antibiotics"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ENephrogenic systemic fibrosis is primarily associated with exposure to \u003Cstrong\u003Egadolinium-based contrast media\u003C/strong\u003E in patients with reduced kidney function. The risk is highest in patients with an estimated glomerular filtration rate below 30 mL/min/1.73m\u00b2.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENon-steroidal anti-inflammatory medicines\u003C/strong\u003E can affect kidney function but do not cause nephrogenic systemic fibrosis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIodinated contrast media\u003C/strong\u003E may cause contrast-induced nephropathy but not nephrogenic systemic fibrosis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBeta-lactam antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E can cause hypersensitivity reactions but are not associated with this condition\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAminoglycoside antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E can cause nephrotoxicity but do not trigger nephrogenic systemic fibrosis\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe condition was first recognised in 1997 and has led to significant changes in how gadolinium-based contrast agents are used in medical imaging, particularly in patients with kidney disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Gadolinium-based contrast agents can cause nephrogenic systemic fibrosis in patients with impaired renal function","Nephrogenic systemic fibrosis primarily occurs in patients with estimated glomerular filtration rate below 30 mL/min/1.73m\u00b2","Nephrogenic systemic fibrosis causes progressive fibrosis of skin, joints, and internal organs"],"references":["Shamam YM, De Jesus O. Nephrogenic Systemic Fibrosis. 2023 Aug 23. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 33620831.","Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Koeppen, B. M., \u0026 Stanton, B. A. (2018). Renal Physiology E-Book: Renal Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52630"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15027"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52630","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52630"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-03T22:31:06+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-03T22:32:58+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7715"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67174"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt"